Month 1 – Python Basics and Data Manipulation (Summary)

Week 1: Introduction to Python Programming

In this week, I learned the fundamentals of Python programming. I studied variables, data
types, operators, input/output, conditional statements (if-else), and loops (for and while).
These concepts help in writing logical programs and automating tasks. I also created basic
programs such as a temperature converter and a simple calculator.
For the client project, I created a data processing script that calculates the average
temperature from a dataset. This helped me understand how Python can be used for basic
data analysis tasks.

Python Script:

temperatures = [30, 32, 31, 29, 33, 34, 30]
total = sum(temperatures)
count = len(temperatures)
average = total / count
print("Temperature Readings:", temperatures)
print("Average Temperature:", average, "°C")

Concepts Used
 Variables
 Lists
 Arithmetic operators
 Built-in functions (sum(), len())

Week 2: Data Structures and Functions

During this week, I learned about important Python data structures such as lists, tuples,
dictionaries, and sets. I also studied functions, lambda functions, recursion, and list
comprehension, which help in organizing and simplifying code.
In the hands-on tasks, I practiced data transformations such as calculating the sum of
squares and filtering values. For the client project, I developed a data cleaning script that
removes duplicate values and filters unwanted data, which is an important step in data
preprocessing.

# Remove duplicates and filter numbers greater than 10
data = [5, 10, 15, 20, 10, 5, 25, 30]
# Remove duplicates
unique_data = list(set(data))
# Filter values greater than 10
filtered_data = [x for x in unique_data if x > 10]
print("Original Data:", data)
print("Unique Data:", unique_data)
print("Filtered Data (>10):", filtered_data)
Concepts Used
 Lists
 Sets
 List comprehension
 Data filtering

Week 3: NumPy and Pandas for Data Manipulation

This week focused on data manipulation using NumPy and Pandas. I learned about NumPy
arrays, mathematical operations, and broadcasting, which are useful for numerical
computations.
I also studied Pandas DataFrames and Series, along with indexing, filtering, and grouping
data. For the client project, I worked with a dataset to remove missing values and calculate
averages, which helped me understand real-world data cleaning and analysis.

import pandas as pd
# Sample dataset
data = {
"Name": ["A", "B", "C", "D", "E"],
"Score": [85, None, 90, 88, None]
}
df = pd.DataFrame(data)

print("Original Dataset:")
print(df)
# Remove missing values
clean_data = df.dropna()
# Calculate average score
average_score = clean_data["Score"].mean()
print("\nCleaned Dataset:")
print(clean_data)
print("\nAverage Score:", average_score)
Concepts Used
 DataFrames
 Removing missing values
 Mean calculation

Week 4: Data Visualization

In this week, I learned how to visualize data using Matplotlib and Seaborn. I studied
different types of plots such as line plots, bar charts, scatter plots, histograms, heatmaps,
and pairplots.
For the client project, I created a data visualization dashboard to analyze relationships
between different features in a dataset. The dashboard included scatter plots and
histograms, which help in understanding patterns and trends in the data.

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
# Sample dataset
data = {
"Hours_Studied": [1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8],
"Scores": [50,55,60,65,70,75,80,85]
}

df = pd.DataFrame(data)
# Scatter Plot
sns.scatterplot(x="Hours_Studied", y="Scores", data=df)
plt.title("Study Hours vs Scores")
plt.xlabel("Hours Studied")
plt.ylabel("Scores")
plt.show()
Concepts Used
 Scatter plot
 Data visualization
 Feature relationship analysis

